# Cursor Rules — WC 2026 Predictor

## Project overview
Hybrid tabular + GNN pipeline predicting WC 2026 attacker performance.
Stack: Python 3.11, PySpark, Azure Blob Storage, torch-geometric, XGBoost, click.
Purpose: portfolio project demonstrating Databricks, Azure, GNNs, OOP pipeline design.

## Structure
- `pipeline/ingestor.py` — FBref scraping, Azure uploads
- `pipeline/transformer.py` — Spark feature engineering
- `pipeline/graph_builder.py` — PyG graph construction
- `pipeline/model_runner.py` — LOTO CV, XGBoost, GNN, hybrid
- `pipeline/pipeline.py` — orchestrator
- `cli.py` — click entry point only, no logic

## Rules for suggestions

### Always do
- Type hints on every function signature
- Docstring on every class and public method
- Use `logging` not `print()` in pipeline code
- Use `F.col()` and `pyspark.sql.functions` imports for all Spark operations
- Check `_already_cached()` before any FBref scrape
- Add reverse edges in any edge_index construction:
  `edge_index = torch.cat([edge_index, edge_index.flip(0)], dim=1)`
- Join player data on FBref player ID strings, never on name strings
- Load secrets from environment variables via python-dotenv, never inline

### Never do
- Never suggest `train_test_split` — all CV is leave-one-tournament-out
- Never write Azure connection strings, account names, or keys inline
- Never put business logic in `__init__` — only `self.x = x` assignments
- Never suggest flat scripts — everything lives inside a class method
- Never suggest random splits for model evaluation
- Never scrape FBref without first checking the local cache in `data/raw/`

## OOP conventions
- One class per file
- Methods should do exactly one thing
- If a method exceeds ~30 lines, suggest breaking it into helpers
- Private helpers prefixed with `_`

## PyTorch Geometric conventions
- `Data` objects always have: `x` (node features), `edge_index`, `y` (targets)
- Attach `player_id_map` dict as a custom attribute for embedding lookup
- `edge_index` shape is always [2, num_edges]
- Use `SAGEConv` (GraphSAGE) as the default convolution — more robust than GCN
  for variable-degree graphs

## Spark conventions
- Always call `.printSchema()` after loading a new DataFrame
- Use `.withColumn()` for derived columns, not UDFs unless necessary
- Write feature tables as Parquet, not CSV
- Load feature tables into pandas before model training — don't train in Spark

## Testing
- Test at minimum: cache check logic, feature table join row count,
  edge_index shape validation, LOTO fold count
- Use pytest, fixtures for reusable DataFrames
